  The recovery manager uses ARIES (Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability) to ensure atomicity by determining the order in which transactions are undone, which pages were delayed at the time of the crash, and the LSN from which the redo should start. The redo pass starts from a position determined during analysis and performs a redo, repeating the process to bring the data base to the state it was in before the crash. The undo pass rolls back transactions that were completed at the time of the crash. To ensure isolation, it requires that data items accessed in a mutually exclusive manner; that is, while one transaction is accessing a data item, no other transaction can modify that data item. The most commonly used method to implement this requirement is to allow a transaction to access a data item only if it is currently holding a lock on that item. We introduced the concept of locking in Section 17.9.
