  The goals of Online Transaction Processing (OLTP) and data analytics are fundamentally different. OLTP is designed to handle high-volume, real-time transactions, ensuring that the system can process and respond to numerous requests quickly and accurately. Its primary goal is to provide immediate service and support to users, ensuring that transactions are completed efficiently and without delay.
  
  On the other hand, data analytics aims to extract insights and patterns from large datasets to make informed decisions. It involves analyzing historical data to identify trends, predict future outcomes, and optimize operations. Data analytics is often used to support strategic planning, marketing, and decision-making processes, rather than immediate transaction processing.
  
  In summary, OLTP focuses on real-time transaction processing, while data analytics focuses on extracting insights from historical data to support strategic decision-making.
